<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">

<head>
  <meta charset="UTF-8">
  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
  <title>SkillsCraft</title>
  <script src="https://cdn.tailwindcss.com"></script>
</head>

<body class="bg-gray-100">

  <!-- Navbar -->
  {{>navbar}}

  <div class="flex">

    <!-- Sidebar -->
    {{>html_sidebar}}

    <!-- Main Content -->
    <div class="ml-0 md:ml-64 w-full">
      <div class="container mx-auto p-6">

        <!-- Section: Core Concepts of HTML -->
        <section class="mb-12">
          <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold mb-6">HTML Forms</h1>

          <!-- Concept 1: Introduction to HTML -->
          <div class="mb-8"></div>
          <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold mb-4">The &lt;form&gt; Element</h2>
          <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">
            The HTML &lt;form&gt; element is used to create an HTML form for user input:
          </p>
          <pre id="code-block"class="bg-gray-100 p-4 rounded-lg border border-gray-300 mb-4">
&lt;form&gt;
<i>Form Elements</i>
&lt;form&gt;
                        </pre>
                     
      </div>

      <!-- Concept 2:  HTML DOCTYPE -->
      <div class="mb-8">
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold mb-4">The &lt;input&gt; Element</h2>
        <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">
          An &lt;input&gt; element can be displayed in many ways, depending on the type attribute.
        </p>
                 
      </div>
      <br>
      <!-- Concept 3: Basic HTML Heading -->
      <div class="mb-8">
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold mb-4">Text Fields</h2>
        <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">
          The &lt;input type="text"&gt; defines a single-line input field for text input. </p>
        <pre class="bg-gray-100 p-4 rounded-lg border border-gray-300 mb-4 ml-6 mr-6">
<form id="code-block1">
  &lt;label for="fname"&gt;First name:&lt;/label&gt;&lt;br&gt;
  &lt;input type="text" id="fname" name="fname"&gt;&lt;br&gt;
  &lt;label for="lname"&gt;Last name:&lt;/label&gt;&lt;br&gt;
  &lt;input type="text" id="lname" name="lname"&gt;
</form>
                        </pre>
     <button id="copy-button1" class="absolute bg-blue-600 text-white py-1 px-3 rounded hover:bg-blue-500 focus:outline-none focus:ring focus:ring-blue-300">
                Copy
            </button>
                    
                     
      </div>
      <br>
      {{!-- Concept 4 : HTML Paragaraphs --}}
    
      {{!-- Concept 5 :About HTML  --}}
      <div class="mt-6 mb-8">
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold mb-4">The &lt;label&gt; Element</h2>
        <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">
Notice the use of the <label> element in the example above.
<strong>

The &lt;label&gt; tag defines a label for many form elements.
</strong>
<br>
<br>
<hr>
The &lt;label&gt; element is useful for screen-reader users, because the screen-reader will read out loud the label when the user focuses on the input element.
<br>
The &lt;label&gt; element also helps users who have difficulty clicking on very small regions (such as radio buttons or checkboxes) - because when the user clicks the text within the &lt;label&gt; element, it toggles the radio button/checkbox.<br>

<br>
Inspect an HTML Element:
Right-click on an element (or a blank area), and choose "Inspect" to see what elements are made up of (you will see both the HTML and the CSS). You can also edit the HTML or CSS on-the-fly in the Elements or Styles panel that opens.</p>
        
      </div>
      </section>

      <!-- HTML Code Editor Section -->
      {{>editor}}

    </div>
  </div>
  </div>
{{>footer}}
  <!-- JavaScript to Handle Sidebar Toggle and HTML Editor -->
  <script>
         document.getElementById('copy-button1').addEventListener('click', function () {
            const codeBlock = document.getElementById('code-block1').innerText;
            navigator.clipboard.writeText(codeBlock).then(() => {
                alert('Code copied to clipboard!');
            }).catch(err => {
                console.error('Error copying code: ', err);
            });
        });
  </script>

</body>

</html>